{{Infobox book <!-- |italic title = (see above) --> | name = A Latin Dictionary Founded on Andrews' Edition of Freund's Latin Dictionary | image = | caption = | alt = | author = [[Charlton T. Lewis]] and [[Charles Short (lexicographer)|Charles Short]] | title_orig = Harpers' Latin Dictionary: A New Latin Dictionary Founded on the Translation of Freund's Latin-German Lexicon Edited by E. A. Andrews | orig_lang_code = | title_working = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = United States | language = English | series = | subject = | genre = | published = 1879 | media_type = Print ([[hardcover]]) | pages = 2019 | awards = | isbn = 978-0-19-864201-5 | oclc = 1063568 | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = | wikisource = A Latin Dictionary }} '''''A Latin Dictionary''''' (or '''''Harpers' Latin Dictionary''''', often referred to as '''Lewis and Short''' or '''L&S''') is a popular English-language [[lexicography|lexicographical]] work of the [[Latin language]], published by [[Harper (publisher)|Harper and Brothers]] of [[New York City|New York]] in 1879 and printed simultaneously in the United Kingdom by [[Oxford University Press]].
==History==
The work is usually referred to as Lewis and Short after the names of its editors, [[Charlton T. Lewis]] and [[Charles Short (lexicographer)|Charles Short]]. It was derived from the 1850 English translation by [[Ethan Allen Andrews (lexicographer)|Ethan Allen Andrews]] of an earlier Latin-German dictionary, ''Wörterbuch der Lateinischen Sprache'', by the German [[Philology|philologist]] [[Wilhelm Freund]], in turn based on [[Immanuel Johann Gerhard Scheller|I.J.G. Scheller]]’s Latin–German dictionary of 1783. The Andrews translation was partially revised by Freund himself, then by [[Henry Drisler]], and was finally edited by Short and Lewis.<ref>See the advertisement of the book itself, [[s:A Latin Dictionary|available on WikiSource]].</ref>
The division of labour between the two editors was remarkably unequal. Short, a very thorough but slow worker, produced material for the letters A through C, but B and C were lost by Harpers, meaning that his work now only appears in the letter A (216 pages), while Lewis, who worked in the time he could spare from his law practice, was solely responsible for the entries beginning with the letters B through Z (1803 pages).<ref>{{Cite journal | volume = 20 | issue = 4 | pages = 349–66 | last = Sypher | first = Francis Jacques | title = A History of ''Harpers' Latin Dictionary'' | journal = Harvard Library Bulletin | date = October 1972 | url = http://nrs.harvard.edu/urn-3:FHCL:486241 }}</ref> In 1890 Lewis published a heavily abridged version the dictionary, entitled ''An Elementary Latin Dictionary,'' for the use of students. Sometimes called the ''Elementary Lewis,'' it is still in print today.
The adoption of the book by Oxford University Press was the result of the failure of its own project to create a new Latin-English dictionary in 1875. [[Henry Nettleship]] and [[John Eyton Bickersteth Mayor|John Mayor]] had been commissioned to produce a new Latin dictionary based on a fresh reading of the sources, but after Mayor withdrew from the project, Nettleship was unable to complete it on his own; he eventually published his research as notes on Lewis and Short.<ref>{{Cite journal | issn = 2160-5076 | volume = 32 | pages = 66–81 | last = Stray | first = Christopher | title = Lex Wrecks: A Tale of Two Latin Dictionaries | journal = Dictionaries: Journal of the Dictionary Society of North America | accessdate = 2013-11-29 | year = 2011 | url = http://muse.jhu.edu/journals/dictionaries/v032/32.1.stray.html }} {{Cite book | publisher = Clarendon Press | last = Nettleship | first = Henry | title = Contributions to Latin lexicography | location = Oxford | accessdate = 2013-10-29 | year = 1889 | url = https://archive.org/details/contributionstol00nettuoft }}</ref> While the Press had earlier published John Riddle’s 1835 translation of Scheller’s Latin–German dictionary, this was a much more expensive book. The Press thus adopted ''Harpers' Latin Dictionary'' as a stopgap measure, paying Harper and Brothers 10 per cent royalties.<ref>{{Cite book |edition = 2 |publisher = Oxford University Press |isbn = 9780199580316 |pages = xi–xvii |editors = P.G.W. Glare (ed.) |last = Stray |first = Christopher |title = Oxford Latin dictionary |chapter = The Oxford Latin Dictionary: A Historical Introduction |location = Oxford |year = 2012 |url = http://www.oupjapan.co.jp/upload/samples/9780199580316_Introduction.pdf |access-date = 2013-10-19 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130327035452/http://www.oupjapan.co.jp/upload/samples/9780199580316_Introduction.pdf |archive-date = 2013-03-27 |dead-url = yes |df = }}</ref> Harper and Brothers sold its rights to the [[American Book Company (1890)|American Book Company]] in 1899, shortly before its bankruptcy.<ref>{{Cite book | publisher = Oxford University Press | isbn = 9780199568406 | last = Louis | first = W. Roger | title = History of Oxford University Press: Volume III: 1896 to 1970 | location = Oxford | year = 2013 | page = 428 }}</ref>
From the time of its publication, many scholars have criticized the dictionary for its errors and inconsistencies.<ref>For example: * {{Cite journal | issn = 0017-3835 | volume = 6 | issue = 2 | pages = 212–213 | last = Dilke | first = O.A.W. | title = Final -e in Lewis and Short | journal = Greece & Rome | date = October 1959 | jstor = 641434 | doi=10.1017/s0017383500013863 }}
* {{Cite journal | issn = 0009-840X | volume = 48 | issue = 6 | pages = 212–214 | last = Dunbabin | first = R.L. | title = Notes on Lewis and Short | journal = The Classical Review | date = December 1934 | jstor = 701476 | doi=10.1017/s0009840x00066154 }}
* {{Cite journal | issn = 0009-840X | volume = 49 | issue = 1 | pages = 9–12 | last = Dunbabin | first = R.L. | title = Notes on Lewis and Short (Continued) | journal = The Classical Review | date = February 1935 | jstor = 697220 | doi=10.1017/s0009840x00066646 }}
* {{Cite journal | issn = 0009-840X | volume = 50 | issue = 5 | pages = 165–166 | last = Fletcher | first = G.B.A. | title = More Notes on Lewis and Short | journal = The Classical Review | date = November 1936 | jstor = 705935 | doi=10.1017/s0009840x00077210 }}
* {{Cite journal | issn = 0009-840X | volume = 8 | issue = 1/2 | pages = 25–27 | last = Inge | first = W.R. | title = Annotations in Lewis and Short's Lexicon | journal = The Classical Review | date = February 1894 | jstor = 693788 | doi=10.1017/s0009840x00187207 }}
* {{Cite journal | issn = 0018-0750 | volume = 8 | issue = 19 | pages = 326–344 | last = Ingram | first = John K. | title = Etymological Notes on Lewis and Short's Latin Dictionary | journal = Hermathena | year = 1893 | jstor = 23036732 }}
* {{Cite journal | doi = 10.2307/288076 | issn = 0002-9475 | volume = 14 | issue = 3 | pages = 362–364 | last = Kirkland | first = J.H. | title = Some Errors in Harpers' Latin Dictionary | journal = The American Journal of Philology | year = 1893 | jstor = 288076 }}
* {{Cite journal | doi = 10.2307/288106 | issn = 0002-9475 | volume = 14 | issue = 2 | pages = 216–225 | last = Knapp | first = Charles | title = Corrections and Additions to Lewis and Short in Connection with Aulus Gellius | journal = The American Journal of Philology | year = 1893 | jstor = 288106 }}
* {{Cite journal | issn = 0018-0750 | issue = 68 | pages = 32–45 | last = Laidlaw | first = W.A. | title = Lewis and Short: Some Corrigenda and Addenda | journal = Hermathena | date = November 1946 | jstor = 23037562 }}
* {{Cite journal | doi = 10.2307/287803 | issn = 0002-9475 | volume = 20 | issue = 2 | pages = 169–185 | last = Leeper | first = Alexander | title = Notes on Lewis and Short's Latin-English Lexicon | journal = The American Journal of Philology | year = 1899 | jstor = 287803 }}
* {{Cite journal | issn = 0009-840X | volume = 50 | issue = 1 | pages = 9–10 | last = Maguinness | first = W.S. | title = Notes on Lewis and Short | journal = The Classical Review | date = February 1936 | jstor = 705705 | doi=10.1017/s0009840x00075375 }}
* {{Cite journal | doi = 10.2307/287815 | issn = 0002-9475 | volume = 15 | issue = 3 | pages = 348–355 | last = Moore | first = Frank G. | title = Corrections and Additions to Lewis and Short | journal = The American Journal of Philology | year = 1894 | jstor = 287815 }}</ref> Because of various circumstances, however, no replacement was attempted until 1933, with the ''[[Oxford Latin Dictionary]]'', which was completed in 1983.
The dictionary's [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.04.0059 full text] is available on-line from the [[Perseus Project]]. Lewis and Short is also available for offline consultation, by means of various applications.
==Comparison with other dictionaries== Among classicists, Lewis and Short has been largely superseded by the ''[[Oxford Latin Dictionary]]'', called the '''''OLD''''' for short. Lewis and Short incorporated material from existing Latin dictionaries; the ''OLD'', by contrast, started from scratch, following procedures similar to those of the well-regarded ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]''. Thanks to the increased availability of modern editions, the ''OLD'' editors had access to a larger variety of classical works.<ref>{{Cite journal |issn=0026-8232 |volume=83 |issue=2 |pages=223–25 |last=Mueller |first=Janel M. |authorlink=Janel Mueller |title=Review of Oxford Latin Dictionary by P. G. W. Glare |journal=Modern Philology |date=1985-11-01 |jstor=437022 |doi=10.1086/391471 }}</ref> Although classicists still consult Lewis and Short, they tend to prefer the ''OLD''.
On the other hand, Lewis and Short remains a standard reference work for medievalists, renaissance specialists, and early modernists, as the dictionary covers Late and Medieval Latin, if somewhat inconsistently. The ''OLD'', when used on its own, rarely meets their needs, since it was decided early in the ''OLD'''s planning that the work would not encompass works written later than AD 200. A few exceptions were made for especially important texts from the late classical period, such as [[Augustine of Hippo|Augustine]]'s ''[[City of God (book)|De Civitate Dei]]'', but for periods later than that the ''OLD'' is considerably less useful. The ''[[Dictionary of Medieval Latin from British Sources]]'' supplements the ''OLD'' for medieval usage of Latin words.
In cases where Lewis and Short do not answer a medieval usage question, J. F. Niermeyer's ''Mediae Latinitatis Lexicon Minus'' often supplies an answer. The ''Lexicon Minus'' was completed in 1976 by C. van de Kieft after Niermeyer's death, and has since become a standard reference work.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi=10.1093/ehr/XCIII.CCCLXVIII.655 |issn=0013-8266 |volume=93 |issue=368 |pages=655–656 |last=Brooke |first=C. N. L. |authorlink=Christopher N. L. Brooke |title=Review of Mediae Latinitatis Lexicon Minus by J.F. Niermeyer; C. van de Kieft |journal=The English Historical Review |accessdate=2013-10-19 |date=July 1978 |url=http://ehr.oxfordjournals.org/content/XCIII/CCCLXVIII/655.full.pdf+html?frame=sidebar }}</ref> More recent editions of the ''Lexicon Minus'' have corrections and expansions; also, in later editions all words are defined in English, French and German, making it of greater international importance than Lewis and Short. The ''Glossarium ad scriptores mediae et infimae latinitatis'' completed in 1678 by [[Charles du Fresne, sieur du Cange|Charles du Fresne]] (commonly referred to as '''''Du Cange''''' after the author's title, the ''Sieur du Cange'') is now less frequently used, as Niermeyer's ''Lexicon Minus'' incorporates much of its information.
On occasion people confuse Lewis and Short (or '''L&S''') with '''Liddell and Scott''', its [[Greek language|Greek]] counterpart, entitled ''[[A Greek–English Lexicon]]''. The 1945 and later editions of Liddell and Scott are commonly referred to by the abbreviation '''''LSJ''''' after the names of its editors [[Henry Liddell|Liddell]], [[Robert Scott (philologist)|Scott]] and the editor of the 1945 revision, [[Henry Stuart Jones|Jones]].
